-- 
U.K. Stocks Advance; BSkyB Gains as News Corp. Wins Approval

-- B y   A d r i a   C i m i n o
-- 
2011-03-03T17:09:46Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-02/aviva-plc-balfour-beatty-lloyds-u-k-irish-equity-preview.html
U.K. stocks rose the most in more
than a month as companies from  Aviva Plc (AV/)  to  Balfour Beatty Plc (BBY) 
announced earnings that exceeded analysts’ estimates.  Aviva and Balfour Beatty gained 1.7 percent and 3.9
percent, respectively.  British Sky Broadcasting Group Plc (BSY)  jumped
3 percent after the U.K. government’s Culture Secretary  Jeremy Hunt  approved News Corp.’s plan to buy the 61 percent of BSkyB
that it doesn’t already own.  The  FTSE 100 Index (UKX)  climbed 1.5 percent to 6,005.09 at the
4:30 p.m. close in London, its first advance this week. Even so,
the gauge has fallen 1.4 percent from its highest level this
year on Feb. 8 as investors speculated that the political unrest
that began in Tunisia and  Egypt  will spread from  Libya  to
countries on the Arabian peninsula, pushing  oil prices  higher
and weakening the outlook for economic growth. The FTSE All-
Share Index increased 1.4 percent today and Ireland’s ISEQ Index
advanced 0.3 percent.  “Broadly positive economic data this week has so far
helped the markets shrug off any Middle East contagion worries
and uncertainty over rising oil prices,” Yusuf Heusen, senior
sales trader at IG Index in  London , wrote.  In the U.S., initial jobless claims unexpectedly declined
last week to the lowest level since May 2008, pointing to a
strengthening labor market, according to a Labor Department
report. The productivity of U.S. workers increased in the fourth
quarter at a faster pace than forecast as companies sought to
pare costs to preserve profits, another report showed.  BSkyB, Aviva, Cobham  BSkyB rose 3 percent to 823 pence.  Rupert Murdoch ’s News
Corp. won U.K. government approval for its 7.8 billion-pound
($12.7 billion) bid to take full control of BSkyB after agreeing
to spin off the Sky News channel to allay its rivals’
competition concerns.  Rival U.K. media companies declined.  Daily Mail & General
Trust Plc (DMGT) , the publisher of the Daily Mail newspaper, slid 3.1
percent to 540 pence, its biggest drop since November.
Broadcaster  ITV Plc (ITV)  fell 3.1 percent to 90.6 pence.  Trinity
Mirror Plc (TNI) , which publishes the Daily Mirror, sank 22 percent to
66 pence even after full-year operating profit rose 17 percent.  Aviva advanced 1.7 percent to 457.3 pence. The U.K.’s
second-biggest insurer by sales reported full-year operating
profit of 2.55 billion pounds. That beat the 2.49 billion-pound
estimate of nine analysts surveyed by Bloomberg.    Cobham Plc (COB)  increased 7.5 percent to 224.6 pence. The
world’s largest maker of airborne-refueling equipment announced
a share buyback program after full-year profit rose 3.7 percent
on orders including work on U.S. military programs. Cobham won
contracts on projects including the F-35 Joint Strike Fighter
aircraft, the CH-53K Super Stallion heavy-lift cargo helicopter
and the Aegis surveillance and fire control radar system.  Kazakhmys, Balfour Beatty    Kazakhmys Plc (KAZ)  added 3.5 percent to 1,487 pence.
Kazakhstan’s biggest copper miner plans to raise about $250
million selling shares in  Hong Kong  as the London-traded company
seeks to broaden its investor base. Kazakhmys will sell new
shares amounting to a 2 percent stake, Chief Executive Officer
Oleg Novachuk said today without giving a timeframe.  Balfour Beatty rose 3.9 percent to 354.7 pence. Britain’s
biggest builder reported a 20 percent gain in full-year pretax
profit before one-off items to 319 million pounds, boosted by
its acquisition of Parsons Brinckerhoff Inc. That beat the mean
estimate of 11 analysts surveyed by Bloomberg for 317 million
pounds of pretax profit.    Whitbread Plc (WTB)  gained 3.9 percent to 1,708 pence after HSBC
Holdings Plc raised its recommendation on the owner of Costa
Coffee shops and Premier Inn budget hotels to “overweight”
from “neutral.”    IMI Plc (IMI)  jumped 6.6 percent to 943 pence, its largest jump
since May last year. The world’s biggest maker of pneumatic
controls said full-year sales rose to 1.91 billion pounds from
1.79 billion pounds in 2009. The company said it’s
“optimistic” to make good progress in 2011.  AMEC, Tullow Oil    AMEC Plc (AMEC)  surged 5.4 percent to 1,190 pence. The London-
based oil and gas engineer predicted that its business will grow
in 2011, while maintaining margins greater than 9 percent. The
company said earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation and
amortization rose 30 percent last year to 271.8 million pounds
on sales that gained 16 percent to 2.95 billion pounds.    Tullow Oil Plc (TLW)  climbed 3.9 percent to 1,466 pence. The
company announced that its appraisal well in the Deepwater Tano
license off the coast of  Ghana  has found oil in excellent
quality sandstone reservoirs. Tullow described its Owa-1
discovery as a “major light oil find.”    Taylor Wimpey Plc (TW/)  increased 5.1 percent to 41 pence. The
U.K.’s second-largest homebuilder by volume reported a 2010
profit after the company sold homes at higher prices. Taylor
Wimpey generated 259.3 million pounds of net income in 2010,
compared with a loss of 640.4 million pounds in 2009.    Spirent Communications Plc (SPT)  lost 1.8 percent to 152.5 pence.
The maker of testing gear for phone equipment said net income
fell to $79.1 million in 2010 from $91.2 million in 2009 because
of higher taxes.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Adria Cimino in Paris at 
 acimino1@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
